[1
Date: 11 Oct 2000
From: Chris Griot <griot@freesurf.ch>
Source: Reuters, 11 Oct 2000 [edited

An age-old French sausage-making tradition looked set to change after the
government said it would ban cow intestines from food because of fears it
might transmit [the etiologic agent of mad cow disease (BSE, Bovine
Spongiform Encephalopathy) to humans.
French Farm Minister Jean Glavany said the government had decided to accept
the opinion of French food safety agency AFSSA that cattle intestine posed
a risk of transmitting to humans the fatal brain-wasting disease known as
BSE. The decision would come nearly a year after AFSSA first recommended a
ban on cow intestines due to concerns over BSE.
Glavany said the ban would affect processed meat products using cow
intestine as an envelope. He cited andouillette, a traditional short, fat
sausage made from entrails, and large sausages as among those affected by
the ban.
The minister said it would be possible to continue to make these products
either by using synthetic intestine, by importing intestine from countries
not affected by BSE -- such as those in Latin America 足 or by using pig or
sheep intestine. This raised the issue of banning cow intestines from
countries having BSE.
The French charcuterie, or processed meats, federation said the ban would
affect some 70 companies producing 15 000 tons, or 1.5 billion French
francs' ($199.5 million) worth, of food each year using the targeted
ingredients.
Gerard Le Tyrant, the federation's head, said it would ask the government
to postpone the measure for several months while its members sought
solutions to the ban. While he admitted that pig intestine could replace
cow intestine in most products, he said 4 or 5 French companies may be put
out of business because they had no alternative to using cow intestine. He
explained these companies used veal intestine to produce delicacies such as
Lyon-style andouillette. "These traditions date back to the Middle Ages --
they're as old as France itself," Le Tyrant told Reuters. "Products that
are representative of French gastronomy are simply going to disappear."
The minister also said the ban was designed to protect consumer safety and
the government would revisit the issue depending on how France's own BSE
epidemic evolved. "It (BSE) is still with us and is growing steadily, and
we should take all the precautions scientists recommend until this epidemic
begins to drop," he said.
The farm ministry reported on Tuesday that the number of French cases of
BSE had more than doubled to 62 this year from 30 last year.
BSE is believed to spread to people by infected food products, emerging as
a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (nvCJD). Around 70 people in
Britain and 2 in France have died from nvCJD.
-足
Chris Griot
<griot@freesurf.ch>
