[2
Date: 11 Oct 2000
From: Chris Groit <griot@freesurf.ch>
Source: Bloomberg News, 10 Oct 2000 [edited

French Agriculture Minister Jean Glavany stressed his commitment to a ban
on British beef imports in order to prevent BSE from spreading. "The more
time passes, the more arguments support our decision" not to lift the ban,
Glavany said. The French food safety agency advised against ending the
embargo in October last year stating there could still be a risk of beef
carrying BSE.
As a result of the ban "French cattle is a thousand times less affected" by
BSE than their British counterparts, Glavany said, adding 90 other non
EU-countries held on to the embargo as well.
The European Commission ruled in August last year to lift the worldwide ban
in place since 1996, leading to compliance by all European Union member
states with the exception of France.
Earlier today the French government said it discovered 2 new cases of BSE
in the country, raising to 62 the number of infected animals found this year.
The cows were slaughtered and burned, along with 156 others from herds they
had been in contact with, in accordance with health regulations, the
Agriculture Ministry said.
The cows, born in 1995 and 1996, were probably infected by contaminated
animal-based feeds, according to a group formed to monitor BSE.
European Union countries introduced more stringent food measures in 1996 on
concern they contained the BSE agent, which may cause a fatal brain disease
in humans.
--
Chris Griot
